  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN139.1-kilavi">piriviṭai melinta talaimaka ṭōḻikkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What SHE who had weakened in the time of separation said to the confidante.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN139.1">
              <l>tuñcuvatu pōla viruḷi viṇpaka</l>
              <l>vimaippatu pōla miṉṉi yuṟaikoṇ</l>
              <l>ṭēṟuvatu pōlap pāṭuciṟan turaii</l>
              <l>nilaneñ cuṭka vōvātu cilaittāṅ</l>
              <l>kārtaḷi poḻinta vārpeyaṟ kaṭainā</l>
              <l><supplied>ḷī</supplied>ṉṟunā ḷulanta vālā veṇma<supplied>ḻai</supplied></l>
              <l>vāṉṟō yuyarvarai yāṭum vaikaṟaip</l>
              <l>putalē raṇinta kāṇpiṉai kālait</l>
              <l>taṇṇaṟum paṭunīr māntip patavaruntu</l>
              <l>veṇpuṟak kuṭaiya tirimarup piralai</l>
              <l>vārmaṇa loruciṟaip piṭavaviḻ koḻuniḻaṟ</l>
              <l>kāmar tuṇaiyō ṭamartuyil vatiya</l>
              <l>varakkuniṟa vuruvi ṉīyaṉ mūtāy</l>
              <l>parappi yavaipōṟ pā<supplied>a</supplied>yp palavuṭa</l>
              <l>ṉīrvār maruṅki ṉīraṇi tikaḻa</l>
              <l>viṉṉum vārā rāyi ṉaṉṉutal</l>
              <l>yātukoṉ maṟṟavar nilaiyē kātalar</l>
              <l>karuvik kāriṭi yirīiya</l>
              <l>paruva maṉṟavar varutumeṉ ṟatuvē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>On the last day of overflowing rain that poured in full drops, (5)</l>
                <l>becoming dark as if sleeping, flashing (1)</l>
                <l>as if blinking so as to split the sky, the sound (2)</l>
                <l>grating excessively as if rising, taking residence, (3)</l>
                <l>[and] resounding over the land thus without stopping, so that [my] heart is in dread, (4)</l>
                <l>at dawn when impure white clouds that died the day</l>
                <l>after giving birth [to it] play on mountains high as to touch the sky, (6f.)</l>
                <l>at the time of such a sight when the bushes are adorned with beauty, (8)</l>
                <l>while the Iralai [deer] with twisted horns, possessing a white back,</l>
                <l>drinks the cool fragrant water that falls, eats Patavu grass</l>
                <l>[and] rests in rightful sleep together with [its] desirable mate</l>
                <l>in the rich shade as the Piṭavu [blooms] open on one side of the overflowing sand, (9-12)</l>
                <l>while cochineals, of a form of vermillion colour,</l>
                <l>spread many together, as if they had been scattered, (13f.)</l>
                <l>[and] glitter, wet ornaments on the side overflowing with water, (15)</l>
                <l>if he does not come even now, [you with] good forehead, (16)</l>
                <l>what then will be his position? [Our] lover, (17)</l>
                <l>[this] is not the season</l>
                <l>that drives away the thunder of the massive rainy season,</l> 
                <l rend="indent4">of which he said: “we will come.” (18f.)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
